      "content": "Colorectal cancer (CRC) commonly spreads to the liver, drastically reducing patient survival. Obesity-related metabolic dysfunction–associated steatotic liver disease (MASLD) increases the risk and severity of CRC liver metastasis by promoting a fibrotic, immunosuppressive tumor microenvironment (TME). This environment is driven by hepatic stellate cells (HSCs) that transform into cancer-associated fibroblasts (CAFs), producing low-molecular weight hyaluronic acid (HA) via HAS2. This HA form activates pathways that support tumor growth and suppress immune responses, including M2 macrophages and exhausted CD8+ T cells. The study found that inhibiting HA synthesis reduced tumor burden in steatotic livers and enhanced anti–PD-1 therapy effectiveness, suggesting that treatment for CRC liver metastasis should be tailored based on whether steatotic liver disease is present.
    },
