      "section_title": "Conclusion",
      "content": "The authors conclude that they have isolated and enriched a human umbilical cord blood-derived non-adherent CD133+ endothelial forming cell population (naEFCs) that express both hematopoietic progenitor and mature endothelial markers, demonstrating functional endothelial capabilities in vitro and in vivo. Unlike early EPCs, these cells lack myeloid markers CD11b and CD14. Extensive molecular analyses revealed ICAM-3 as a unique surface adhesion protein on naEFCs that mediates their rolling and adhesion to activated endothelium under shear stress, distinguishing them from mature endothelial cells. Given their low frequency in circulation and specific adhesion profile, ICAM-3 may be a critical molecule for progenitor cell recruitment to sites requiring vascularization and serves as a promising diagnostic or therapeutic target to modulate aberrant vasculogenesis."
